english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of Gold to the Maitreya Triad of the Golden Hall at Geumjang Temple on Yongdu Mountain
  author: Lee San
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Buddha takes true emptiness as his substance and responsive manifestation as his function. How then would he concern himself with whether the images we fashion crumble or endure, visiting fortune or calamity upon us? Rather, as people follow the two paths of good and evil, so too do they receive the fruits of their deeds. What is there to doubt in such a principle?

    Geumjang Temple stands as a great sanctuary in the southern lands, ancient in its origins though time has weathered its halls. Our Royal Master, the Great Meditation Teacher Buddha-Sun Universal Illuminator of Pure Wisdom, Wondrous Perfection, True Mirror, once wandered in solitude through these mountains. Passing by this temple by chance, he beheld the Maitreya Triad of the Golden Hall, their celestial forms faded and peeling. Moved with compassion, he conceived a vow to restore them and departed.

    When in the eleventh year of the Great Virtue era, in the summer of the year Dingwei, he received the dharma-seat at the Wondrous Lotus Society and ascended to the rank of Royal Master, he chose this temple as his mountain residence. Thus he pursued his earlier vow, offering sixteen pounds of white silver in exchange for five ounces of purple gold and pigments of every hue, providing all necessary funds for the artisans and the great ceremony.

    In the first year of the至大 era, in the year Wushen, he transferred to Zhouqing Temple, entrusting his disciple Meditation Master Hongzhi to continue in residence here and oversee the gilding. In the ninth month of autumn of the second year, Jiryou, the Master journeyed from the capital, entering the temple on the fifteenth day of Jiawu. He engaged the painter and temple master Jicheng of Gaoyuan Temple, who began the work on the twenty-first day of the tenth month, Gengwu. By month's end of the twelfth moon, he had molded clay to repair decay and carved wood to replace rot. Then with purple gold he renewed the forms of the three honored ones, with indigo pearls he renewed their eyes, adorning them anew with flower crowns, jeweled necklaces, and celestial robes. A carved screen was set behind the principal Buddha, upon which a lion rears up to form his seat. From a single log arose a pedestal for the attendant bodhisattvas, upon which lotus flowers unfold to receive their feet. Great stones, hewn and placed, provided the precious platform for the triad—secure and steadfast indeed.

    When in the following February the painting was complete, he invited the assembly of the Myriad Virtue Society to perform the eye-opening ceremony. The work in clay and wood, the artistry of the paintings—all surpassed what came before while preserving the ancient forms.

    The Master reported this to the Royal Master, who sent back these verses:

    *In my aging years one thing has weighed upon my heart—
    that I could not restore the Buddha of Geumjang's Golden Hall.
    Today winds scatter the clouds across empty sky,
    and fire wheels ascend to light the eastern lands.
    Tusita's splendor blooms resplendent here,
    the retinue of Maitreya's assembly surely shall appear.
    Had you not been my companion in that ancient vow,
    how would I know this work has found completion?
    In the three assemblies yet to come,
    this karmic bond shall be proclaimed on one same day.*

    Thus the Master's vow is made manifest. This verse too is recorded here.

    Examining the Records of the Golden Hall, no such hall existed in former times. It was first constructed in the second month of the second year of the Song Chunhua era—our sovereign's eleventh year, the year Xinmao—by the temple master, the Great Master Xuantan of Mingzhen Hongxiao. From that year until now, in the year Gengxu, three hundred and nineteen years have passed. How many abbots have presided during this span? How many pilgrims have come to bow and pay respects? Yet all merely endured and let time pass. Only when our Royal Master beheld the decay did the damaged forms bloom anew with golden faces—is this not the meeting of cause and circumstance?

    Once, in ancient times, the Great Mahakasyapa adorned an ancient Buddha with gold leaf, causing it to shine brilliantly. Through this karmic connection, for ninety-one kalpas throughout the heavens and among humans, his form remained perpetually golden and his mind perpetually joyful. At last, at the Assembly on Spirit Mountain, hearing the Lotus Sutra expounded, he received prediction of Buddhahood and became the Buddha called Light-Radiance Tathagata.

    How then can we measure the future fruit that awaits our Royal Master?

    The Master sent word requesting that this record be made, that it might be transmitted for eternity. Thus I have simply noted down the months and days.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tusita (도솔) refers to the heavenly realm where Maitreya resides; Maitreya's assembly (용화) refers to the future gathering when Maitreya Buddha will teach dharma on earth.
  - key: ''
    value: The three assemblies (삼회) in Buddhist tradition refer to three successive assemblies where Maitreya Buddha will preach the dharma in the future age.
  - key: ''
    value: Mahakasyapa was one of Buddha Shakyamuni's foremost disciples; his act of gilding an ancient Buddha became a model act of devotion that generated karmic benefits over countless ages.
